Introduction

All matter contains energy and energy changes take place when a matter undergoes either a physical or chemical change. Thermodynamics is the study of energy and its transformation. In this chapter, we will focus on thermochemistry, the study of heat change in chemical and physical processes. We will also be looking at why certain physical and chemical changes take place spontaneously.

### Enthalpy and enthalpy changes

The total chemical energy of a substance is called its **enthalpy** (or heat content). Chemical energy consists of kinetic energy and potential energy. The potential energy, due to electrostatic attraction between the particles, is usually the main component of the total chemical energy, [1].

During a chemical reaction, bonds are broken and new bonds are formed. The breaking of bonds requires energy while the formation of bonds releases energy. The energy change that occurs is called the **enthalpy change of reaction**. The symbol is \(\Delta H_{r}\) and the units are \(J\) mol\({}^{-1}\) or \(J\) mol\({}^{-1}\).

As most chemical reactions take place at constant pressure, the heat involved in the process (the flow of thermal energy) can be expressed as \(\Delta H\). Hence, when a reaction vessel feels warm, thermal energy is given off by the reaction and transferred to our hands. At the microscopic level, thermal energy can be represented by the movement of particles. The greater the average kinetic energies of the particles, the greater the amount of thermal energy of the system.

