### Standard conditions and standard states

Besides the physical state of the substances, the enthalpy change of a reaction is also affected by the physical conditions of temperature and pressure. For valid comparison, a set of **standard conditions** have to be specified under which enthalpy changes are measured.

A substance in its normal (most stable) physical state at 298 K and 1 bar is said to be in its **standard state**. E.g. \(\mathrm{I_{2}(s)}\), \(\mathrm{Br_{2}(\mathit{I})}\), \(\mathrm{C_{S}(\mathit{R})}\) (Refer to note below).

The actual enthalpy of an element cannot be measured. Hence, elements in their standard states under standard conditions are assigned zero enthalpy (\(\mathit{H=0}\)).

When the enthalpy change is measured under standard conditions, it is referred to as the **standard enthalpy change** and is represented by the symbol \(\Delta H^{\mathrm{\Theta}}\).

