### Gibbs Free Energy

To predict whether a process is spontaneous, we need to apply the Second Law of Thermodynamics which states that the entropy of the universe increases for a spontaneous change. We have to consider the entropy change that takes place both in the system and in the surrounding.

\[\Delta S_{\text{universe}}=\Delta S_{\text{system}}+\Delta S_{\text{ surrounding}}\]

In chemistry, to simplify discussion, the focus of analysis is on the system. Hence it is more convenient if \(\Delta S_{\text{system}}\) and \(\Delta S_{\text{surrounding}}\) are combined together in a single function known as the change in Gibbs free energy. The derivation is beyond the scope of the syllabus; The change in Gibbs free energy is named after Josiah Willard Gibbs and is given the symbol \(\Delta G\). \(\Delta G\) can be expressed in terms of \(\Delta H\) and \(\Delta S\) of the system:

When \(\Delta G\) is negative (Gibbs free energy is lowered), \(\Delta S_{\text{universe}}\) is positive and vice versa. Hence we can use the sign of \(\Delta G\) to predict if a reaction is spontaneous.

