#### 9.3.2 Calculations of \(\Delta G_{r}\) from \(\Delta G_{t}\)

Like enthalpy change (\(\Delta H\)), Gibbs free energy change (\(\Delta G\)) is a state function. This means that the value that it takes only depends on the state of the substance, and not how it was brought to that state. The'state' is specified by variables such as temperature and pressure. Hence \(\Delta G\) of a reaction can be calculated in a similar way as \(\Delta H\) in Section 3. Likewise, \(\Delta S\) is a state function and \(\Delta S\) of a reaction can also be calculated a similar way.

